<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911014-0177</DOCNO><DOCID>911014-0177.</DOCID><HL>   GenRad Inc. to Post   Third-Quarter Loss;   Begins Restructuring</HL><DATE>10/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7G</SO><CO>   GEN</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)</IN><NS>EARNINGS PROJECTIONS (ERP)</NS><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   CONCORD, Mass. -- GenRad Inc. said it will reportlower-than-expected sales and a third-quarter net loss of $29million to $30 million after restructuring charges.   GenRad said it expected to report a loss from operationsof $6 million to $7 million, a pre-tax restructuring chargeof $15 million for equipment write-downs and severance costs,and an $8 million increase in reserves for excess facilitiesin the weak Silicon Valley real estate market.</LP><TEXT>   Revenue for the period ended Sept. 28 were below $35million, the company said, and orders for automatic testequipment were weaker in international markets than expected.&quot;That softness added to the already weak recessionarydomestic demand&quot; for electronic test equipment, the companysaid.   GenRad said that in response to the slower sales it hasbegun a restructuring of costs including world-wide workforce reductions. President Robert E. Anderson said that&quot;stop-gap measures&quot; such as furloughs and salary reductionsnow in place are inadequate and that GenRad must reduce itsbreak-even point.   In the 1990 third quarter, Genrad had a net loss of$984,000, after a special gain of $5 million, on revenue of$43.5 million.</TEXT></DOC>